The way the inflation is computed matters a lot here. The figure will be the ratio vs the CPI a year ago, which was particularly high in june 19. As a consequence, we will "observe" a very low number, possibly negative, even if the prices remain flat versus the month of May. My guess: CPI flat vs May, means 0.1% decrease. Thus more weight on negative than positive. I don't see much signs of increasing prices or strong decreases compared to last month: covid situation is stabilizing and markets opening again. That adds a bit of chance to an increase. Final choice a 55-55 instead of a 60-40. No strong rational for the %. I think we are going to be very close to the border of the two answers.

The European Commission Spring 2020 forecast, released May 6, predicts 2020 annual inflation at 0.2% for the Euro Area [1]. Ten of the nineteen Euro Area countries saw negative inflation in April, so it is definitely possible. Germany, the largest economy, was at 0.9% in April, but I'd expect that to drop in the coming months due to the delayed impacts of the virus there as compared to Italy, Spain, etc. Is the calculation for the Euro Area simply weighted by the country's GDP or is it done in some other way? I couldn't find a helpful answer.

Revising: Every time inflation has been this low, it's gone below zero. I don't think it'll go below zero because it doesn't seem like fundamentals have changed suddenly enough, so that leaves 0-1% as the proximate best chance.

Growth and inflation are broadly linked in general and in the Eurozone. The only time inflation has dipped below 0 in the last quarter century was in 2014, when energy prices dropped precipitously. This was accompanied by a 5% drop in year-on-year output. FT reports that economic malaise in the Eurozone is starting to lift (https://www.ft.com/content/8ffb5d91-074b-4fd2-8b74-bfbbb60750e7), with growth slowing but output still higher than last year. For the past 4-5 years, Euro inflation has sat comfortably between 1 and 2%, and has only this month dropped below 1. So I'd say it's about even odds that it'll sit on either side of 1, with a slight boost for above, given reversion to the mean and the FT's apparent evidence of improved economic prospects.

Inflation can also come from relative currency pairs losing value and faith of the marketplace - however, euro is near to being a reserve currency - as such - measuring relative strength to other major world currencies - EUR:USD and EUR:GBP, over the past 3 years, seems to have traveled in a defined sideways pattern - no reason to expect a breakout either way in 2020. In contrast to the Argentina peso:USD or :EUR - where the charts reflect a steady erosion in currency value relative to the base currency, and where Main Street wage and price inflation is severe. I used EU inflation rate data to predict June 2020's annual inflation rate with a forecasting algorithm (FB Prophet). If no major events happen that could affect consumer confidence, then we could predict with current inflation rate trends that inflation should be close to 1%. I'm favouring 0.1%-1% because my algorithm predicts 0.9%. However, considering that this is so close to 1%, I can't say much on its accuracy. I would keep my eye out on European consumer behavior, particularly if there's news on changes in the European energy, food, industrial or services sector as proxies to adjust my predictions accordingly.

I think @ajr1000 's approach to the base rate here https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/937713 makes sense - as a minor modification I use data from Jan 2009 onwards, which gives 11, 32, 32, 25 for the answer options. The inflation rate seems to be on a downward trend for the last few months, and given the timeframe of the question I think at this stage it is reasonable to assume that this trend will continue. Measures that could be used by the ECB to bring inflation closer to their target value of close to 2% such as more negative interest rates or more asset purchasing programs seem to become less and less popular with both the public and the committee members at the ECB. In addition it seems that these tools don't have the effect on inflation they used to have, requiring some adjustment of the narrative or a change of approach altogether. I therefore increase the probability of the second lowest bucket from the base rate at the expense of higher inflation buckets.
